observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct:
a. The OIC - Municipal General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant to trace the unreconciled beginning balance, fees and expenses totaling P126,690.79 to determine whether such fees and expenses should be treated as capitalizable or should be expensed outright; 
● 106 parcels of land listed in the CPH issued by MAssO were neither reported in the RPCPPE nor recorded in the books;
● 15 parcels of land listed in the CPH with Original Certificate of Title (OCT) and/or Transfer Certificate of Title (TCT) filed with the MGSO were neither reported in the RPCPPE nor recorded in the books of account; and
● 20 parcels of land with OCT and/or TCT under the name of the Municipality of Pagsanjan were neither recorded in the books nor listed in the CPH.
This is not in keeping with the Sections 111 and 112 of Presidential Decree (PD) No. 1445 and Paragraph 14 of the International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS) 17. As a result, the accuracy and reliability of the Land account reported at P19,981,390.41 in the Statement of Financial Position (SFP) could not be ascertained.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct:
● The OIC - Municipal General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant to trace the unreconciled beginning balance, fees and expenses totaling P126,690.79 to determine whether such fees and expenses should be treated as capitalizable or should be expensed outright; 
● The OIC - Municipal General Services Officer to:
  • Reconcile the results of verification on the 106 parcels of land to determine the status and proper recording in the books; 
  • Expedite the transfer of the title of the identified three parcels of land with Deed of Donation and Letter of Intention to donate the property and subsequently furnish the MAO with copies of the title to facilitate the recording of the same in the books of account; and
  • Conduct investigation on the 17 parcels of land with the Municipality of Pagsanjan listed as its registered owner in the OCT and/or TCT filed with the MGSO but were not found in either the books of account maintained by the MAO or in the CPH provided by the MAssO.

Furthermore, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor, through an issuance of an Executive Order (EO), create an Appraisal Committee to properly appraise the lots acquired through donation as to their fair values at the time of acquisition.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Human Resource and Management Officer (HRMO) to immediately register the unlisted employees and the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Provide a written explanation on the occurrence of: (a) over-remittance of Pag-IBIG premiums and loan amortizations totaling for the month of August, 2023 and (b) abnormal balance of P1,285.99 in the sub-ledger for the Multi-Purpose Loan (MPL) amortization during the month of October, 2023; 
b. Coordinate with the HRMO and reconcile the amount related to contributions withheld for employees not registered with PhilHealth and Pag-IBIG against identified under-remittance each month and remit the same if necessary; 
c. Verify the unremitted prior years PhilHealth and Pag-IBIG premiums totaling P226,116.23 and Due to PhilHealth P200,633.03, respectively, and immediately remit or effect the necessary adjustment, if warranted; and 
d. Henceforth, strictly monitor the monthly withholding and remittance of PhilHealth and Pag-IBIG premiums and/or loan amortizations to avoid accumulation of unremitted balances.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Provide a written explanation on the occurrence of over- and/or under-remittance of the taxes withheld from the employees’ compensation and payments to suppliers and GSIS premiums and loan amortizations; 
b. Analyze the SL accounts of the Due to BIR (2-02-01-010) account under the General Fund (GF) and Special Education Fund (SEF) and Due to GSIS (2-02-01-020), specifically focusing on the payments of employees’ loan amortization for GSIS Financial Assistance Loan (GFAL), Multi-Purpose Loan (MPL) and Computer Loan, which exhibit abnormal debit balances of P19,303.45, P19.26, P34,860.82, P17,031.73 and P10,986.01, respectively, after the posting of the remittances for the month of December, 2023. Draw the corresponding adjusting JEV, if warranted, and furnish the Audit Team for verification; 
c. Verify the unremitted withholding taxes and GSIS premiums and/or loan amortizations, and immediately remit or effect the necessary adjustment, if warranted; and
d. Henceforth, strictly monitor the withholding of taxes and GSIS premiums and/or loan amortizations to avoid accumulation of unremitted balances.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the General Services Office and the Inventory Committee to conduct complete inventory taking of all property. We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the GSO and the Municipal Accountant:
a. to conduct regular reconciliation of their records in order to further decrease the discrepancy and make the necessary adjustments, if warranted; 
b. to prioritize the tracing and verification of the PPE that were unidentified beginning balances of P6,815,407.41 in the inventory report; 
c. to identify and reclassify property to its proper PPE account; and 
d. reclassify those PPEs with a value of less than P10,000.00 and with a life expectancy of more than one year as Inventories and issue Inventory Custodian Slip upon issuance for control and monitoring purposes.
